# Code Quality & Completeness Review

This workflow verifies that code and features are **actually complete** — no 
hidden bugs, no documentation gaps, no untested code, no broken edge cases.

Use this BEFORE marking work done, or when inheriting code from the past.
This is the "holistic health check" that prevents "it looked fine until..."

**When to use:** After implementation is "finished" and before any merge/deploy.

================================================================
1. PRE-REVIEW CHECKLIST
================================================================

Before diving into detailed checks, answer these baseline questions:

□ Code compiles without errors?
□ No TypeScript/ESLint/type errors?
□ Test suite runs without failures? (what's the pass rate?)
□ All console.log/debug statements removed?
□ No commented-out code left in?
□ No TODO/FIXME/XXX comments without context or deadline?

If ANY of these fail, STOP and fix before proceeding.

================================================================
2. IMPLEMENTATION CORRECTNESS REVIEW
================================================================

Verify the code actually implements what was requested, correctly.

REQUIREMENTS VERIFICATION:
□ Does the code do what was asked? (read the original request)
□ Did you miss any requirements?
□ Are there requirements that are partially implemented?
□ Does the implementation match the acceptance criteria?

LINE-BY-LINE CODE REVIEW:
For each function/component:

□ Do the inputs match what callers pass?
□ Do the outputs match what callers expect?
□ Is the logic correct for the happy path?
□ Does it handle all documented inputs properly?
□ Are there obvious bugs (off-by-one, null checks, type mismatches)?
□ Are variable names clear and consistent?
□ Is there dead code that should be removed?
□ Are there any "magic numbers" that should be constants?

CONTROL FLOW:
□ Does every code path return/resolve?
□ Are there unreachable code paths?
□ Is the logic flow obvious or convoluted?
□ Do conditionals cover all cases (if X, else what)?
□ Are loops guaranteed to terminate?

EXAMPLE CHECKLIST:
```
Function: calculateDiscount(price, quantity, coupon)

✓ Handles price = 0? (no division errors)
✓ Handles quantity = 0? (returns 0 discount? 0 price?)
✓ Handles coupon = null / undefined?
✓ Handles negative prices / quantities?
✓ Returns correct type (number, or throws)?
✓ Precision correct for currency (2 decimals)?
✓ Doesn't mutate input parameters?
✓ Performance reasonable (no N² loops)?
```

================================================================
3. ERROR HANDLING & EDGE CASE REVIEW
================================================================

Check if code fails gracefully or crashes silently.

EXPLICIT ERROR HANDLING:
□ What happens on network failure? (is it handled?)
□ What happens on invalid input? (thrown? logged? defaults?)
□ What happens on timeout? (retry logic? fallback?)
□ What happens on API error? (shown to user? logged?)
□ Are all Promise rejections caught?
□ Are all async errors awaited/handled?

EDGE CASES:
□ Empty input ([], "", null, undefined)
□ Single item (list with 1 thing)
□ Large input (1000s of items)
□ Boundary values (min/max, first/last)
□ Concurrent calls (race conditions?)
□ Invalid data types (string instead of number)
□ Missing optional fields
□ All paths through conditionals tested

DEFENSIVE CODING:
□ Input validation at entry points?
□ Type checks (TypeScript or runtime)?
□ Null checks before property access?
□ Array bounds checks?
□ Exception handling for third-party calls?
□ Graceful degradation (doesn't break on one bad item)?

SYMPTOMS OF POOR ERROR HANDLING:
❌ "It works in the happy path, but if X is null it crashes"
❌ "No error logging, so we don't know what went wrong"
❌ "Unhandled promise rejection"
❌ "Silent failure (returns undefined instead of throwing)"
❌ "Generic error message (doesn't help debug)"

================================================================
4. DOCUMENTATION COMPLETENESS REVIEW
================================================================

Verify documentation is complete enough for future developers to understand 
and extend the code.

FUNCTION/COMPONENT DOCUMENTATION:
For each public API (function, component, class, export):

□ Is there a description of what it does?
□ Are inputs documented (parameters, types, examples)?
□ Are outputs documented (return value, type, examples)?
□ Are side effects documented (modifies state? calls API?)?
□ Are errors documented (what exceptions can it throw?)?
□ Are there usage examples?
□ Is there a note if this is performance-sensitive?
□ Is there a note if this has breaking changes?

EXAMPLE (GOOD):
```javascript
/**
 * Calculates the total price with discounts applied.
 * 
 * @param {number} basePrice - Item price in cents
 * @param {number} quantity - Number of items (must be > 0)
 * @param {Coupon|null} coupon - Optional coupon to apply
 * @returns {number} Total price in cents
 * @throws {Error} if basePrice < 0 or quantity <= 0
 * 
 * @example
 * calculateTotal(1000, 2, coupon) // 2000 cents ($20)
 * calculateTotal(1000, 2, null) // 2000 cents (no coupon)
 */
```

EXAMPLE (BAD):
```javascript
// calculate price
function calc(p, q, c) {
  return p * q - (c ? c.amount : 0);
}
```

ARCHITECTURE/DESIGN DOCUMENTATION:
□ Is there a README explaining the module/feature?
□ Are architectural decisions documented (why this design)?
□ Are complex algorithms explained?
□ Are dependencies clearly listed?
□ Is the data flow documented (how does data move)?
□ Are there diagrams for complex flows?

MAINTAINABILITY DOCUMENTATION:
□ Are there comments explaining WHY, not just WHAT?
□ Are there known limitations/future improvements noted?
□ Are there "gotchas" or surprising behaviors documented?
□ Is there a troubleshooting guide?
□ Are external dependencies documented (APIs, libraries)?

CHANGELOG/VERSION DOCUMENTATION:
□ Are breaking changes documented?
□ Are new features documented?
□ Is there a migration guide if needed?

================================================================
5. TEST COVERAGE REVIEW
================================================================

Verify tests actually cover the code and prove it works.

TEST EXISTENCE:
□ Does every public function have at least one test?
□ Do error cases have tests (not just happy path)?
□ Do edge cases have tests?
□ Do integration points have tests?

TEST QUALITY (not just quantity):
A test is good if:
  ✓ It fails when code is broken (test actually proves correctness)
  ✓ It passes when code is fixed
  ✓ It tests ONE behavior (not 5 things at once)
  ✓ It has clear setup, action, assertion
  ✓ It has a descriptive name explaining what it tests

A test is BAD if:
  ❌ It always passes (even if code is wrong)
  ❌ It's unclear what it's testing
  ❌ It depends on test order (brittle)
  ❌ It uses mock objects that hide real problems
  ❌ It tests implementation details, not behavior

COVERAGE METRICS:
□ What % of code is covered by tests? (aim for 80%+)
□ What % of lines are covered? (branches? functions?)
□ What code is NOT covered? (intentional? or forgotten?)
□ Are critical paths covered more thoroughly?

EXAMPLE TEST REVIEW:

GOOD TEST:
```javascript
test('calculateDiscount returns 0 for null coupon', () => {
  const result = calculateDiscount(1000, 2, null);
  expect(result).toBe(0);
});

test('calculateDiscount throws for negative price', () => {
  expect(() => calculateDiscount(-100, 2, null))
    .toThrow('Price must be positive');
});
```

BAD TEST:
```javascript
test('discount function works', () => {
  const x = calculateDiscount(1000, 2, {amount: 100});
  const y = calculateDiscount(500, 1, null);
  expect(x).toBeDefined();
  expect(y).toBeDefined();
});
```

SPECIFIC TEST CHECKLIST:

Unit Tests:
□ Does each function have unit tests?
□ Do tests cover branches (if/else, switch)?
□ Are error cases tested?
□ Are boundary conditions tested?
□ Mock external dependencies properly?

Integration Tests:
□ Do tests verify components work together?
□ Are real (or realistic) data flows tested?
□ Do tests verify API contracts?
□ Are database operations tested?

Edge Case Tests:
□ Empty/null inputs
□ Large inputs
□ Boundary values
□ Concurrent calls
□ Error states from dependencies
□ Timeout/retry scenarios

Snapshot/Visual Tests (if applicable):
□ Are snapshots reasonable (not 1000 lines)?
□ Would a developer understand what changed?
□ Are visual regressions caught?

================================================================
6. CODE QUALITY METRICS REVIEW
================================================================

Verify code quality beyond just "does it work?"

COMPLEXITY:
□ Functions under 50 lines? (most should be)
□ Cyclomatic complexity reasonable? (how many branches?)
□ Nesting depth reasonable? (not 5 levels deep)
□ Are there better ways to simplify?

DUPLICATION:
□ Is code repeated that could be abstracted?
□ Are there similar patterns that should share logic?
□ Is copy-paste used instead of abstraction?
□ Would a shared utility help?

CONSISTENCY:
□ Code style matches the rest of the project?
□ Naming conventions consistent?
□ Similar problems solved in similar ways?
□ No random formatting or weird indentation?

PERFORMANCE:
□ Are there obvious inefficiencies (N² loops, repeated calculations)?
□ Are expensive operations (API calls, DB queries) minimized?
□ Are there memory leaks (listeners not cleaned up, subscriptions not unsubscribed)?
□ Is caching used appropriately?

SECURITY (if relevant):
□ Are inputs validated/sanitized?
□ Are secrets not hardcoded?
□ Are SQL injections prevented (parameterized queries)?
□ Is user data encrypted if needed?
□ Are permissions checked?

================================================================
7. INTEGRATION & ENVIRONMENT REVIEW
================================================================

Verify the code works in the actual environment.

LOCAL TESTING:
□ Does it work on localhost?
□ Does it work in development environment?
□ Have you tested it with realistic data?
□ Have you tested with slow network (throttled)?
□ Have you tested with actual API (not mocked)?

ENVIRONMENT SPECIFICS:
□ Does it work in different browsers (if web)?
□ Does it work on different Node.js versions?
□ Does it work with different database versions?
□ Are environment variables documented?
□ Are there any hardcoded paths/hosts?

DEPENDENCIES:
□ Are all required dependencies listed (package.json)?
□ Are dependency versions locked (no floating versions)?
□ Are there security vulnerabilities in dependencies?
□ Are unused dependencies removed?
□ Do dependency versions work together?

================================================================
8. DOCUMENTATION TESTING
================================================================

Verify documentation is accurate and complete.

README ACCURACY:
□ Does the README match the actual code?
□ Are examples in README actually runnable?
□ Are install instructions correct?
□ Do they work exactly as written?

API DOCUMENTATION:
□ Are all endpoints documented?
□ Are all parameters documented?
□ Are response formats documented?
□ Are error responses documented?
□ Are examples provided and correct?

DEVELOPER ONBOARDING:
□ Can a new developer run the project locally with instructions?
□ Do they know where to start making changes?
□ Are common tasks documented (run tests, build, deploy)?
□ Is the architecture clear?
□ Are there troubleshooting guides?

================================================================
